'''Tom Greenway''' (June 5, 1909&ndash;February 8, 1985)<ref name=ssdi>{{cite web|url=http://ssdi.rootsweb.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/ssdi.cgi|title=[[Social Security Death Index]]|publisher=ssdi.rootsweb.ancestry.com|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[character actor]] of [[film]] and [[television]], whose career, primarily in television [[Western (genre)|westerns]], extended from 1949 to 1965.<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|url=http://italy.imdb.com/name/nm0339281/|title=Tom Greenway|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref>

==Early life==

Greenway was born in [[Booneville, Arkansas|Booneville]] in [[Logan County, Arkansas|Logan County]] northwest of [[Fort Smith, Arkansas|Fort Smith]] in northwestern [[Arkansas]].  During [[World War II]] he served in the [[United States Army Air Corps]]. While on a mission, he was shot down and spent more than a year in [[Italy|Italian]] and [[Germany|German]] [[Prisoner of War|POW]] camps.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/person/28597/Tom-Greenway|title=About this Person: Tom Greenway|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref> Released from military service, he performed on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in [[New York City]], where he procured his [[Social Security number]],<ref name=ssdi/> before he moved into films, where he had many uncredited roles in the early years of his career.<ref name=nyt/>

==Acting career==

Greenway's first appearances were uncredited in two 1949 [[film]]s, ''[[Impact (film)|Impact]]'' and ''Deputy Marshal''. He appeared often as a law enforcement officer. He was an unnamed townsman in the 1952 [[Dale Robertson]] film based on [[Bret Harte]]'s [[short story]], "[[The Outcasts of Poker Flat]]".<ref name=imdb/> 

Greenway appeared twice in 1954-1955 on the [[Rod Cameron]] [[Television syndication|syndicated]] [[television series]] ''[[City Detective (TV series)|City Detective]]''. In 1955, he guest starred in the episode "The Big Genius" of [[NBC]]'s ''[[Dragnet (TV series)|Dragnet]]'', starring and narratged by [[Jack Webb]]. In 1958, Greenway appeared four times on Rod Cameron's second syndicated program, ''[[State Trooper (TV series)|State Trooper]]'', a modern western series. He portrayed Sheriff Bronson in the episodes "Stay Lost, Little Girl", "Dangerous Honeymoon", "Full Circle", and "Death on Wheels". That same year he appeared on [[Pat Conway]]'s ''[[Tombstone Territory]]'' as Kylie in the episode entitled "Geronimo", with [[John Doucette]] as the [[Apache]] Chief [[Geronimo]]. Greenway also appeared in 1958 as Dr. Quinn in "The Dan Hogan Story" of the [[NBC]] western ''[[Wagon Train]]''. In 1959, he portrayed John Sebrey in "Death of a Gunfighter" on [[Richard Boone]]'s ''[[Have Gun - Will Travel]]''. That same year, he played the role of [[rancher]] Frank Chanault in the film ''[[These Thousand Hills]]''.<ref name=imdb/>

Between 1957 and 1960, he appeared in different role in five half-hour episodes of [[CBS]]'s ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', with [[James Arness]]. He appeared in 1961 in the episode "Gamble with Death" on the syndicated [[anthology]] western series, ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', with John Doucette again playing Geronimo. That same year, Greenway guest starred twice on both NBC's ''[[Bat Masterson (TV series)|Bat Masterson]]'' and CBS's ''[[Rawhide (TV series)|Rawhide]]'' in the latter as Hawthorne in "Incident at the Blackstorms". In 1961, Greenway also played warden Binns in the episode "The Return of the Widow Brown" of [[Henry Fonda]]'s series ''[[The Deputy (TV series)|The Deputy]]''. That same year, he also played Glenn Cornell, a used car salesman, in the episode "Very Hard Sale" of NBC's police drama, ''[[87th Precinct (TV series)|87th Precinct]]''. [[Peter Helm]] appeared as Cornell's son, Andy.<ref name=imdb/>

In 1962, he appeared twice on NBC's ''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]''. He guest starred as Henry Sharp in the segment "Don't Wake a Tiger" in Dale Robertson's ''[[Tales of Wells Fargo]]''. He appeared five times between 1960 and 1962 on NBC's ''[[Bonanza]]''. On CBS's ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', Greenway guest starred as Rod Andrews in "The Case of the Howling Dog" (1959) and as Dick Jenkins in "The Case of the Fifth-Millionth Frenchman" (1964).<ref name=imdb/>

Greenway's final video role was in 1965 as a [[marshal]] in the episode "The Verdict" of [[Robert Horton (actor)|Robert Horton]]'s [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series, ''[[A Man Called Shenandoah]]''. Greenway died of a [[heart attack]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], nearly twenty years after his last acting role.<ref name=imdb/>He was survived by his wife, Helen T. Greenway (born 1920) of [[Hemet, California|Hemet]] in [[Riverside County, California|Riverside County]], California.<ref>People Search & Background Check</ref>

